
The active module root has an implicit `start()` function for top-level runtime code.
Imported module roots contribute their public declaration surface without replaying root code. Normal files contribute declarations only.

Page fragments split before HIR.
Runtime fragments remain code.
Compile-time fragments become builder metadata.

## Active-root start

Header parsing captures the active module root's top-level runtime code as a `HeaderKind::StartFunction`.
The implicit `start` header isn't part of dependency sorting.
It's appended after sorted declarations and lowered by AST.

That means top-level declaration order and active-root runtime order stay separate:

- constants, type aliases, structs, choices, function signatures and type annotations can affect dependency sorting
- executable body references don't affect top-level declaration order
- active-root runtime code runs through implicit `start`
- imported-root runtime code and direct fragments are suppressed in the importer
- normal files can't contain top-level runtime statements

## Runtime and const fragments

Active-root page fragments are split like this:

- top-level runtime templates remain runtime code inside `start()`
- `start()` returns runtime fragment strings in source order
- active-root top-level const templates fold in AST into compile-time fragments
- each compile-time fragment records a runtime insertion index
- builders merge compile-time fragments into the runtime fragment list
- HIR doesn't carry compile-time page fragments or a separate ordered start-fragment stream

This keeps HIR backend-facing and semantic.
Page assembly stays with builders.

## Simple shape

The wrong shape defines a named constant template and later emits it at top level:

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    page_title #= "Demo"

    intro #= [$md:
        # Hello
    ]

    message = [:
        Runtime content
    ]

    [intro]
    [message]
]

Here `intro` is a named constant template and a top-level reference to it is an ordinary runtime expression. This does **not** make `intro` a compile-time page fragment. The correct compile-time fragment form is the direct active-root-only const-template shown below:

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    page_title #= "Demo"

    #[$md:
        # Hello
    ]

    message = [:
        Runtime content
    ]

    [message]
]

This direct top-level const-template form is active-root-only. It must fold and
may become a compile-time page fragment.

A reference to `message` at top level is runtime code inside the implicit `start`. A constant template referenced through an ordinary runtime top-level expression doesn't become a compile-time fragment merely because its value can fold.

Templates assigned to variables or returned from functions are not page fragments by themselves. Only direct top-level const-template forms of the shape shown above in an active HTML module root contribute compile-time page fragments.

## Imported root suppression

Header preparation assigns each file one explicit role: active module root, imported module root or normal. Both root roles may contain `export:` declarations, but only the active root produces a start header and fragment activity. An imported root's top-level runtime body is skipped before AST, so importing a public API cannot execute or emit the imported module's page content.

## Builder merge

Builders receive resolved const top-level fragments and `ModuleRootActivity`, including the runtime fragment count.
They own route-level assembly.

The HTML builder merges compile-time fragments into the runtime fragment list, creates runtime fragment slots for active-root `start()` output and then assembles the final page artifacts.

HIR only models the runtime code needed to produce runtime fragments.
It doesn't need to know that the HTML builder is making a document.

This fragment plan is shared by HTML-JS and HTML-Wasm. The selected execution artifact and runtime bridge differ, but the builder-owned insertion and hydration order doesn't.

Reactive mounting is separate and remains an HTML-JS-only runtime concern.

## Why this split matters

The split prevents three common bugs:

- treating compile-time page fragments like runtime HIR statements
- making HIR own HTML page assembly
- letting backends parse top-level template syntax again to recover fragment order

AST folds and records fragment metadata.
HIR lowers runtime templates.
Builders assemble project artifacts.
Each layer stays small.
